thread.title: NFL Week 7 overreactions: Are Cowboys finished?
thread.title_full: NFL Week 7 overreactions: Are Cowboys finished?

author: tennessean
title: NFL Week 7 overreactions: Are Cowboys finished?
text:
Tackling five overreactions from Week 7:
The Dallas Cowboys are done
Sure, the outlook appears grim for the Cowboys after a 27-20 loss Sunday against the Giants dropped them to last place in their division, but this year’s NFC East is different. There’s no clear-cut favorite, and even though the Cowboys have lost four in a row, they’re just 1.5 games off the lead.
Only 8.3% of teams that started the season 2-4 since 1990 went on to make the playoffs, so the Cowboys aren’t exactly playing with odds on their side.
But Dallas has an elite offensive line and a resurgent running game, tools the team can use to scrap out a couple of victories as long as it takes care of the ball.
USA TODAY
Armour: Jerry Jones' enabling and excuses just as bad as Hardy's behavior
Consider this: The Cowboys suffered three back-breaking interceptions from quarterback Matt Cassel (one returned for a TD) and gave up a 100-yard kickoff return for a score in the second half Sunday, but they still had a chance to win on the road against the now first-place Giants (4-3).
As long as the Cowboys can hang in these next few games, their playoff hopes remain alive – albeit on life support.
And if Romo returns Week 11 against the Miami Dolphins – the first game he is eligible to play after being placed on injured reserve/designated to return list – to his previous form, Dallas could make a late postseason charge.
But to get there, it needs to limit turnovers, run the ball like it did Sunday and somehow find a way to win.
USA TODAY
50 things we learned in Week 7 of the NFL season
The Pittsburgh Steelers gave their season away with a loss against the Kansas City Chiefs
It looked like a trap game, smelled like a trap game and sure felt like one, too.
But as disappointing as Sunday’s 23-13 loss against Kansas City was, Pittsburgh is still alive in the AFC North.
And when you consider that the Steelers (4-3) have won three of their last five games since quarterback Ben Roethlisberger went down with a knee injury, it’s clear to see that Pittsburgh did what it had to do while he was gone.
Get all the latest news on the Pittsburgh Steelers! Check out USA TODAY Sports' SteelersWire ! That changes in Week 8.
The Steelers have a huge showdown against the first-place Cincinnati Bengals (6-0) at home on Sunday, and a victory would be a massive momentum boost. Roethlisberger, who was questionable against the Chiefs but didn’t play, is expected back and that obviously makes them much better.
Pittsburgh still has a hold on the sixth and final projected playoff spot in the AFC, but if it wants to be a legit AFC contender, a win over the Bengals is one the Steelers need to have.
The San Francisco 49ers should bench Colin Kaepernick
It has been a nightmare season for San Francisco’s quarterback.
But even after Kaepernick completed just 13 of his 24 passes Thursday night for a meager 124 yards and no touchdowns, while getting sacked six times, the Niners should stay put.
Kaepernick is still just 27 years old and has all the physical traits you would want in a quarterback. It’s the environment around him that has been an issue.
USA TODAY FANTASY SPORTS
Fantasy football waiver wire: Who can fill Arian Foster's void?
FOX Sports had a report Sunday that Kaepernick’s confidence is “completely shot” and that in the San Francisco locker room he’s “on an island.” When you factor in that this Kaepernick’s first season under new head coach Jim Tomsula and offensive coordinator Geep Chryst, it’s easy to see why there have been some struggles.
Backup Blaine Gabbert isn’t the answer for San Francisco.
The 49ers need to do everything they can to put Kaepernick in a system that makes him feel comfortable and highlights his skill set. That he worked out this offseason with former St. Louis Rams quarterback Kurt Warner, with whom Kaepernick shares practically no traits, shows that the Niners want him to be something that he’s not: a traditional pocket passer.
Kaepernick has had some brutal performances this season. In three games against the Arizona Cardinals, Green Bay Packers and Seattle Seahawks, he has completed 35 of his 68 passes for 351 yards, zero touchdowns and five picks.
There’s no doubt this is a rebuilding year for the 49ers, but it’s time to help boost their quarterback’s confidence. Not bench him.
Rex Ryan is under fire in Buffalo for the Bills' struggles. (Photo: Kirby Lee, USA TODAY Sports)
The Buffalo Bills made the wrong choice in hiring Rex Ryan
This has not been the season the Bills envisioned.
They were a 9-7 team that just missed the playoffs, brought in an energetic and aggressive head coach in Rex Ryan and added a bunch of pieces this offseason.
After Sunday’s loss in London against the Jacksonville Jaguars, there’s no doubt this year has been a disappointment, but it’s too early to call the season a bust.
USA TODAY
Chargers fans feel like they are falling into Black Hole with possible move
Buffalo now sits at 3-4 and in last place in the AFC East, this after starting 2-1 with impressive victories over the Indianapolis Colts and Miami Dolphins.
As with any transition, it takes time. And while the Bills have a defense loaded with talent and an offense with speed and play-making ability, quarterback play has been spotty, at best. With starter Tyrod Taylor missing the last two games, EJ Manuel has bombed.
Buffalo has also been an undisciplined team that has made senseless mistakes and has been penalized far too much. Some of those mistakes can be corrected, but they have also been trademarks of Ryan’s teams. There’s a lot of football left, so it’s only fair to give Rex a pass – for now – but this team does need to show improvement in the second half of the season.
The St. Louis Rams are a playoff team
It was an impressive victory on a lot of fronts, especially with rookie running back Todd Gurley III looking more and more like the real deal.
But the Rams still have a long way to go.
Part of the reason why St. Louis should be only be considered a mild contender is because of the conference it plays in.
The Carolina Panthers (6-0) and Atlanta Falcons (6-1) both play in the NFC South, and if current trends continue, it’s looking more and more like the runner-up of the division crown will claim one of the NFC’s two wild-card spots.
USA TODAY
Bell: Mike Zimmer's Vikings look ready to set sail for playoffs
Then there’s the NFC North, where the Packers (6-0) should roll to the division crown, but the upstart Vikings (4-2) appear to be improving each week.
But then there’s the NFC West, where the Rams play. The Cardinals, whom the Rams beat 24-22 in Week 4, look like the favorite to win the division. But the Seahawks, whom the Rams defeated 34-31 in Week 1, have a championship pedigree and have been in this position before.
There’s a lot of competition for the postseason.
St. Louis may eventually make the playoffs. It has a dominant defense and dynamic skill position weapons.
But until the Rams show that they can consistently stack performances like Sunday’s win against the Cleveland Browns and not lose the head-scratching contest against the Redskins like they did in Week 2, it’s just too early to put them in the contender category.
